		<item>
		<title>SEC warns that celebrity cryptocurrency endorsements may be illegal</title>
		<link>https://arstechnica.com/?p=1198561</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 02 Nov 2017 20:31:45 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Timothy B. Lee]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Policy]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[bitcoin]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[cryptocurrency]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Floyd Mayweather]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Paris Hilton]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://arstechnica.com/?p=1198561</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Floyd Mayweather and Paris Hilton could be in hot water for paid endorsements.]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="rss-wrap">
<figure class="intro-image intro-left"><img src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/6009103709_1df9cce337_o.jpg"><p class="caption" style="font-size:0.8em"><a href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/6009103709_1df9cce337_o.jpg" class="enlarge-link" data-height="480" data-width="720">Enlarge</a> <span class="sep">/</span> Boxer Floyd Mayweather has done paid endorsements for little-known cryptocurrencies. (credit: <a rel="nofollow" class="caption-link" href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/65456139@N07/6009103709/in/photolist-aa1ebn-bqGqY4-9XPmH7-9XPnD1-qG9oJg-eiouSy-9XLKJ2-bNVVbe-rahF9T-nwsrY9-9XLEaa-9XPu9j-MzDdb3-o3BciS-xjbn54-ojUut9-9XLAcV-9XPAB9-9XPxh5-9XPkPs-nh1FH1-bm95dE-9XLsPP-bz3Yii-grojbQ-bm95f1-9vacN8-xjbnJF-Ebdz4c-DdumAj-grojcb-grod8g-oVo1xn-wJrqoq-d1H9HJ-grodFR-grodnz-grodnV-grodfv-dZ5P6Z-s7JiW8-pBFqW-s7JiY2-qbT75-wRJTgs-grodvF-88maqr-xtRqf7-gkcrB1-Pcdsho">So Max O</a>)</p>  </figure><div><a name="page-1"></a></div>
<p>The Securities and Exchange Commission has issued a statement warning celebrities that they may be violating the law if they make paid endorsements of cryptocurrencies without disclosing the payments.</p>
<p>Just a few months ago, there would have been no need for such a warning because there were very few celebrities endorsing blockchain products (though Mike Tyson has been <a href="https://www.coindesk.com/mike-tyson-bitcoin-atm-hit-with-scam-accusations/">endorsing Bitcoin products</a> since at least 2015). But with billions of dollars flooding into initial coin offerings, celebrities like Floyd Mayweather and Paris Hilton have begun promoting new cryptocurrencies on social media.</p>
<p>Readers of Ars will be shocked to learn that these celebrity-endorsed blockchain technologies have not exactly been the cream of the crop. A <a href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/laurashin/2017/09/25/as-founder-faces-possible-jail-time-an-inside-look-at-lydiancoin-paris-hilton-endorsed-cryptocurrency/#746abd8e7cca">September investigation by Forbes</a> reported that the Hilton-endorsed currency, called LydianCoin, was founded by a man "being sued by at least four former employees for harassment and discrimination" and who is facing possible jail time related to domestic violence allegations.</p>
</div><p><a href="https://arstechnica.com/?p=1198561#p3">Read 8 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href="https://arstechnica.com/?p=1198561&comments=1">Comments</a></p><div class="feedflare">
